It just feels very OTT to me, with it coming across as desperately trying to come across as technical and "intelligent" while it just seems very aimless to me.
I don't mind some wank, but if it is going to be wanky I prefer a bit more grounding than everything being a fucking solo. An example of a "bad" wankery album I like is Beyond Creation's debut. It has all the noodling, but regularly slows it down, and whenever they have one instrument showing off they tone down the other to give it a bit of weight. E.g. if the bassist is going apeshit, the rhythms focus on being groovier.
https://youtu.be/pMtTOMotq7g
FF feels like they just can't take a moment to realise that sometimes having more notes crammed into as small a space as possible makes it lose all impact. Compared to BC it has to be a million times faster, everyone must be trying to re-make flight of the bumblebee at once, and try to get all the bald headed music reviewers stroking their chin rather than make an actually good song.

Really it just sounds like something I'd expect Brain Drill to make but with the pretentiousness ramped up to a million percent.

Stage manager guy here. Two things to consider...
There's not much work to do in temrs of PR or business relations. I'm assuming you're American, I don't know how the IRS deals with the status of musician/artist, but it's generally considered a liberal profession so the paperwork isn't the biggest deal. You could do it all by yourself, given you've followed a short training course. There are ways to learn how to position yourself as a musician properly, doing the paperwork, networking, joining a scene, a label, etc. Leave your personality at the door because it's the least important thing when what you want to do is work.
The music industry is not the most competitive environment. There are places that look for muscians to book shows. If you're good enough, you can go basically everywhere, booking artists is a low-risk high-reward endeavor (which makes it difficult for artists to earn a living as well). That's if you do live shows. If you just make music in your home to release on the Internet, that's another story.
Finally, if your goal is to be famous or rich, tough shit because some people still don't know who Jimi Hendrix is. You can't possibly make a living out of music, some of the biggest names out there are broke as shit. You like your job as a musician or you quit and do carpentry or whatever. That's how it goes. That's why I'm a stage manager now, and I was lucky, and it's far from the safest job, but it brings food on the table.

>Gary Numan
I think Numan's right in his interpretation that Bowie was at a low point when Numan was the new big thing. The 80s were Bowie's worst decade IMO, so it probably wasn't fun to see a disciple doing so well what he couldn't, right then at least. Bowie found himself again in the 90s, but it's too bad he couldn't look past himself and support Numan.

>Axl Rose
Rose is a dickhead, so no trouble there.

>Elton John
The Liberace comparison is warranted, but IMO not such a bad thing, really. Idk how much of an influence Bowie had on Elton, but it seems like it was just the clothes, which are the least important part. Elton's best album is Honky Chateau, which is a totally stripped down, earthy, folky/country-ish album, so I don't see Bowie's point.

>McCartney/Beatles
I knew this comment, and I don't see it as Bowie disliking them. What he was saying was, The Beatles had a huge influence on their contemporaries, but much less of an influence on modern bands than The Velvet Underground, which is striking given how much bigger they were. His point was, artists doing radical things tend to have a larger influence on the future.

>JAMC
This one's disappointing, and his insult toward them sucks. At the same time, while IMO Psychocandy is an amazing album, nothing they did afterward was particularly good.

Started playing guitar at the age of 24 without an music experience, both aucoustic and electric almost 1 year ago on my own. If you're starting here's what to expect if you want to get somewhere.
>Learn basic music theory, I read 'Music theory for dummies' in about 6 months, very usefull for any instrument. Don't stress too much about memorizing scales, instead memorize circle of fifths and order of sharps and flats, and your good to go.
>spend hours searching youtube and internet in general for good lessons, 80% is shit fragile ego people who just want to show off. Rule of thumb if you don't understand or learn anything from the video while you paid attention it's their fault for being shitty teachers.
>Learn the fretboard, don't waste too much time with people talking about magical patterns and shapes that 'OpEN uP tHe FrEtboARD' instead be disciplined and learn to play the natural notes on every string, 1 note a day, then learn all the notes per fret for the first 12 frets 1 fret a day so this will take 12 days. Then you combine both exercises, each time your finger lands on a note be slow and mindfull of all the other notes of that fret. Keep doing this as part of your daily exercise routine until your third eye opens. (still working on this myself but getting close)
>Keep up the learning tempo, if you find yourself doing the same boring exercises again and again that you've already mastered you're not getting better. Time to learn new theory, scales, rythm whatever.

Honestly you could throw a dart at any of the theory books and not really go wrong, ONLY as long as you read multiple texts. >>114315733
It is simply a ceiling for your whole track. You are pushing the loudness towards a limit, and everything above that limit gets cut off. If you push too hard it sounds distorted, if you push it to the sweet spot you achieve loudness and a coherent mix.

posts.com:
>>114338656
>Can the Boome MIDI Translator do this?

The Pro version does support logical functions, so I suppose you might be able to accomplish it in there.

Think about what you need here: You need a counter which you set the value of by pressing the bank up/down buttons to increment/decrement, then you need a bunch of conditional logic which checks the value of the counter and executes different commands from the 6 main buttons depending on the counter value. That could be done for maybe two or three counter values (representing two or three possible banks) using nested IF-THEN statements in Bome's MIDI Translator but it would get messy as hell if you want to add more banks than that, so what you need to look at is if MIDI Translator supports other logical constructs, like switch/case statements instead.

Would be easier to do in Max or PD probably which will have switch/case logic, and if you use Ableton there might even be a Max4Live device that exists already to do what you need

>>114341373

Doing it on the controller itself would need firmware changes, and while (for example) the BCR2000 turned out to have enough accessible flash memory to allow it to be converted into the Zaquencer it's not something that can be relied upon for every controller. You'd need to research what microprocessor and supporting hardware is inside the controller, although some of that might be guessed by examining firmware upgrade packages from the manufacturer.

Easier route is an intermediary, that sits on your computer in the MIDI chain between the controller and your DAW and acts as the controller's additional intelligence. As I mentioned, see if Bome's MIDI Translator can do more complex logic than simple IF-THEN, and if it can then you can get it to do what you want. If it can't, then you're either limited to using IF-THEN in Bome's which will get ugly if you want lots of banks, or you're creating your own intermediary in some other MIDI-aware environment, either way you'll be a shitload more experienced by the end of it all.

>Elvis Costello Live 1977 Chicago
>First generation pop-punk, British Power Pop
This has been released under the titles Armed and Dangerous, as well as Exit, but this is the actual soundboard recording used for the WXRT "Unconcert" broadcast in 1978. (Called Unconcert because it was sponsored by 7-Up, The "Un-Cola") Believe it or not, Tom Petty and The Heartbreakers were the opening act at this show. This was just before Elvis Costello and The Attractions made their debut on Saturday Night Live, subbing for The Sex Pistols who cancelled. (THANKS, MALCOLM!) My Aim is True had just been released, but This Year's Model was just a few months away. (Songs from TYM were played at this show)
When you listen to this concert, you'll understand immediately why Elvis Costello and The Attractions were considered a "Punk" band, and why the first generation of punk rockers adopted them as their own until 1980.

Again, no video. My apologies.

Radiohead’s success can be tracked through Creep, OK Computer, Kid A and In Rainbows. Keep in mind I don’t think they’re literally the greatest band of all time by any stretch, but in the realm of pop / rock music, they proved themselves to be interesting and original enough to demand a level of respect.

Creep was a catchy, timeless pop song that covered a universal thought that everyone could resonate with.

The Bends was a decent follow-up that sounded different to Pablo Honey while upping the songwriting quality.

OK Computer was a realisation of songwriting ability (for pop music standards) while honing in on some thoughtful ideas about society (for pop music standards).

Kid A was controversial enough (for pop music standards) of a musical-shift while still keeping the intellectual streak (for pop music standards) of OK Computer running.

In Rainbows’ maturity and refinement of songwriting + the originality of the distrubutional approach to the album solidified their status in rock / pop music history as dedicated and forward-thinking musicians (for pop music standards).

I have to disagree even though I can understand where you are coming from.
MCR were really coming into their own and making a sound that was uniquely them even if they can still be categorized as "emo" music from the mid 2000s with some obvious influences like queen, maiden, post hardcore, and some not so obvious influences like whatever obscure bands they were into growing up or got into in their later years. Not for nothing, the debut was alright for a debut, not bad but there are some moments where Gerard's voice is indistinguishable from all the other post hardcore vocalists who had a sort of whining inflection to their singing that was really high pitched and like their nuts were being squeezed hard, whilst wearing the tightest skinny jeans possible.
Their debut still had signs/elements of what was to come but not yet known at the time, the emphasis on melodic and heavy riffs and singing.
That is too vague of a descriptor since that can describe so many other bands spanning a ton of genres but MCR were moving away from cliches of the post hardcore era/scene and coming into their own, adopting the theatrics and flare, rising above just another post hardcore esque/adjacent band and making albums.
They just kept on building from the last album and reworking what worked while not only keeping it fresh but skimming the fat.
The singles do not sound out of place imo, every album has the hits that outshine the rest of the album but MCR prove to be consistently brilliant songwriters since their other songs hold their own.
Every song on that album has great songwriting and structure, hooks and melodies, the singles just have a more concentrated form of that.
Tldr. I disagree but feel free to read my explanation, I think the album is great

Now by popular demand! A list of some of the songs Zep stole from other artists:

"Babe I'm Gonna Leave You" - A folk song by Anne Bredon, this was originally credited as "traditional, arranged by Jimmy Page," then "words and music by Jimmy Page," and then, following legal action, "Bredon/Page/Plant."
"Black Mountain Side" - uncredited version of a traditional folk tune previously recorded by Bert Jansch.
"Bring It On Home" - the first section is an uncredited cover of the Willie Dixon tune (as performed by the imposter Sonny Boy Williamson).
"Communication Breakdown" - apparently derived from Eddie Cochran's "Nervous Breakdown."
"Custard Pie" - uncredited cover of Bukka White's "Shake 'Em On Down," with lyrics from Sleepy John Estes's "Drop Down Daddy."
"Dazed And Confused" - uncredited cover of the Jake Holmes song (see The Above Ground Sound Of Jake Holmes).
"Hats Off To (Roy) Harper" - uncredited version of Bukka White's "Shake 'Em On Down."
"How Many More Times" - Part one is an uncredited cover of the Howlin' Wolf song (available on numerous compilations). Part two is an uncredited cover of Albert King's "The Hunter."
"In My Time Of Dying" - uncredited cover of the traditional song (as heard on Bob Dylan's debut).
"The Lemon Song" - uncredited cover of Howlin' Wolf's "Killing Floor" - Wolf's publisher sued Zeppelin in the early 70s and settled out of court.
"Moby Dick" - written and first recorded by Sleepy John Estes under the title "The Girl I Love," and later covered by Bobby Parker.
"Nobody's Fault But Mine" - uncredited cover of the Blind Willie Johnson blues.
"Since I've Been Lovin' You" - lyrics are the same as Moby Grape's "Never," though the music isn't similar.
"Stairway To Heaven" - the main guitar line is apparently from "Taurus" by Spirit.
"White Summer" - uncredited cover of Davey Graham's "She Moved Through The Fair."
"Whole Lotta Love" - lyrics are from the Willie Dixon blues "You Need Love."

posts.com:
3.5 is roughly blackpink to itzy (who are 4th)
4.5 started in '21
5th is likely SMnGG, maybe YGnGG if it doesn't tank

Generations are shaped by thematic/musical/industry changes. Big3/4 groups are almost always the marker points and rarely does a small company break into new sounds that shape groups following them; BTS was a notable example as half of 3.5genbg's are just BTS clones, same with BP in 4/4.5.

This is why Twice (3gen) aren't a marker point; no distinguishing factors that cause changes. Groups like NewJeans, while having a new sound that might influence the next gen, aren't markers, as the defining characteristic of the 4.5th gen is oversaturation with generic groups, as a backdrop for high budget groups. LSF and NJ are both the latter; regardless of quality, they stand out among the nugus.
